-- ============================================

INSERT INTO questions (subject_id, question_text, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation, topic, difficulty) VALUES
(1, 'Read the passage carefully and answer the question that follows: "The old man sat under the ancient baobab tree, its massive trunk bearing witness to centuries of change. Children played at his feet, their laughter rising like birds into the fading afternoon light. His eyes, clouded with age yet sharp with memory, followed their movements with the patience of one who has learned that youth must find its own way. The tree had stood through drought and flood, through peace and war, through times when the village prospered and times when it struggled. Now, as the sun painted the sky in shades of orange and purple, the old man felt the weight of all those years - not as burden, but as the accumulated wisdom of lives lived and lessons learned. The children would soon grow, some leaving for the city, some perhaps for countries they could not yet imagine. But the tree would remain, and perhaps, so would he, rooted in this soil that had given him everything." The old man''s feeling about the weight of years is best described as:', 
 'A sense of accumulated wisdom and perspective', 'A burden he wishes to escape', 'Regret for lost opportunities', 'Resentment toward the young', 'A', 
 'The passage explicitly states he feels it "not as burden, but as the accumulated wisdom of lives lived and lessons learned."', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'In the same passage, the children''s laughter is compared to birds. This comparison emphasizes:', 
 'The light, free, and natural quality of childhood joy', 'The noise children make', 'The small size of children', 'The desire to fly away', 'A', 
 'The simile suggests natural freedom and lightness, not just noise or size.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The baobab tree in the passage functions primarily as a symbol of:', 
 'Continuity and endurance through changing circumstances', 'The danger of remaining in one place', 'The need for progress', 'Natural beauty', 'A', 
 'The tree''s endurance through various changes represents continuity and stability amid flux.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The phrase "youth must find its own way" suggests the old man believes:', 
 'That each generation must learn through its own experience', 'That children should be left alone entirely', 'That guidance is useless', 'That the young will make mistakes', 'A', 
 'This implies belief in experiential learning - wisdom can''t simply be transferred.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The passage''s setting at sunset contributes to its mood by:', 
 'Evoking reflection on endings and the passage of time', 'Creating excitement about nightfall', 'Suggesting danger approaching', 'Indicating the story''s conclusion', 'A', 
 'Sunset traditionally symbolizes reflection, endings, and temporal passage, matching the contemplative mood.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The old man''s observation that some children might leave for "countries they could not yet imagine" suggests:', 
 'Awareness of how life paths diverge beyond current comprehension', 'Disapproval of emigration', 'Certainty they will all leave', 'Ignorance of geography', 'A', 
 'This shows recognition that children''s futures hold possibilities beyond current understanding.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'Read the passage and answer: "The harmattan wind arrived without warning, carrying dust from distant deserts. It slipped through cracks in windows, under doors, into lungs and eyes. For weeks, the world would wear a grey veil, the sun a pale coin in a hazy sky. Children wrapped themselves in multiple layers, their breath forming small clouds as they walked to school. Market women pulled scarves over noses and mouths, bargaining as always but with voices muffled. The wind was an invisible visitor that made itself felt everywhere - in the cough that lingered, in the skin that cracked, in the longing for the cool rains of June that were still months away." The primary effect of the harmattan described is:', 
 'An all-encompassing presence affecting all aspects of life', 'A minor inconvenience quickly forgotten', 'A purely visual phenomenon', 'A seasonal celebration', 'A', 
 'The passage shows the wind affects everything from breathing to commerce to emotional state.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'In the harmattan passage, the sun described as "a pale coin" suggests:', 
 'Reduced visibility and intensity due to dust', 'Increased brightness', 'The sun''s value', 'Approaching night', 'A', 
 'The comparison to pale coin indicates diminished appearance through dust haze.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The phrase "longing for the cool rains of June" indicates that harmattan is experienced as:', 
 'A dry season that creates desire for its opposite', 'A pleasant change', 'A brief interlude', 'The best time of year', 'A', 
 'The longing for rain shows harmattan is experienced as lack of what will come later.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'Read: "The examination hall was a study in contrasts. Some candidates wrote furiously, their pens racing against time, pages filling with carefully constructed arguments. Others sat paralyzed, staring at questions that seemed written in a foreign language, their months of preparation evaporating like morning mist. The invigilator''s footsteps echoed at regular intervals, a metronome marking the passage of time that for some moved too fast and for others not fast enough. Outside, the world continued its normal rhythms - birds sang, cars honked, traders called - but inside, time had taken on a different quality, compressed and expanded simultaneously by anxiety and hope." The phrase "their months of preparation evaporating like morning mist" suggests:', 
 'That stress can temporarily block access to knowledge', 'That they hadn''t studied enough', 'That the questions were unfair', 'That morning is a bad time for exams', 'A', 
 'The simile indicates knowledge is present but temporarily inaccessible due to pressure.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'In the examination passage, the invigilator''s footsteps function as:', 
 'A reminder of time passing and pressure mounting', 'A distraction from concentration', 'A comforting presence', 'A signal of authority', 'A', 
 'The regular footsteps emphasize time''s passage in the pressure-filled environment.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The contrast between inside and outside the hall emphasizes:', 
 'The isolating intensity of the examination experience', 'The unfairness of testing', 'That life continues normally elsewhere', 'The need for better soundproofing', 'A', 
 'The outside world''s normalcy highlights the unusual, intense experience within.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'Read: "The city at dawn was a different creature from the city at noon. Before the heat intensified, before the crowds flooded the streets, before the noise reached its daily crescendo, there was a brief hour when Lagos belonged to the early risers alone. The air, still relatively cool, carried the smell of fresh bread from bakeries that had worked through the night. A few okadas zipped past, their riders heading to early shifts. Women set up their breakfast stalls, arranging fried yam and akara with practiced efficiency. In this liminal hour between night and full day, there was a sense of possibility, of a world not yet fully formed, before the city''s notorious energy became overwhelming rather than exhilarating." The phrase "Lagos belonged to the early risers alone" suggests:', 
 'A temporary experience of the city different from its crowded daytime reality', 'That others are excluded from the city', 'That early risers own the city', 'That the city is empty at dawn', 'A', 
 'This indicates a brief period when the city can be experienced differently, not literally owned.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The passage describes dawn in Lagos as a time of:', 
 'Possibility and relative calm before daily intensity', 'Danger and uncertainty', 'Boring inactivity', 'The worst traffic', 'A', 
 'The description emphasizes possibility, calm, and anticipation before daily rush.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The mention of bakeries working "through the night" suggests:', 
 'The continuous economic activity supporting the city', 'That bread is only available at dawn', 'That night workers have no rest', 'The inefficiency of bakeries', 'A', 
 'This shows the 24-hour cycle of work that makes city life possible.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'Read: "His grandmother''s stories were not mere entertainment. They were maps - coded guides to navigating a world that could be hostile to those who forgot their origins. Through tales of clever tortoises and greedy hyenas, of spirits who rewarded the kind and punished the cruel, she transmitted values that no school textbook contained. When she spoke of the girl who married a spirit and found herself in a world where nothing was what it seemed, she was teaching about the dangers of surface appearances. When she told of the hunter who shared his last meal with a stranger who turned out to be a god in disguise, she was instructing in the virtue of hospitality. The children who gathered at her feet absorbed lessons they would spend lifetimes unpacking." The author uses the metaphor of stories as "maps" to emphasize that they:', 
 'Provide guidance for navigating life''s challenges and moral choices', 'Show physical locations', 'Are outdated and unreliable', 'Lead to hidden treasure', 'A', 
 'Maps guide navigation - stories guide moral and practical navigation through life.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The grandmother''s teaching method can be characterized as:', 
 'Indirect, using narrative to convey values experientially', 'Direct instruction through lectures', 'Punishment for wrong behavior', 'Reward for correct answers', 'A', 
 'Stories teach indirectly, allowing listeners to internalize lessons through engagement.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'The phrase "lessons they would spend lifetimes unpacking" suggests the stories are:', 
 'Rich with multiple meanings that unfold with experience', 'Too complicated to understand', 'Quickly forgotten', 'Only for children', 'A', 
 'This indicates depth that reveals itself gradually through life experience.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'Read: "Technology has transformed Nigerian banking in ways unimaginable a generation ago. The elderly man who once queued for hours at the bank now transfers money with a few taps on a phone. The market woman who feared banks as places that would swallow her savings now saves through mobile money, watching her balance grow via SMS. Yet this transformation has not touched everyone equally. In rural areas with poor network coverage, in communities where elderly customers distrust digital systems they cannot see, the old ways persist. The result is a country where a grandmother may prefer buried savings while her grandson trades cryptocurrencies - two economies, two relationships with money, coexisting uneasily in the same nation." The passage''s main idea is:', 
 'That technological change proceeds unevenly, creating different experiences within one country', 'That Nigerian banking is completely modernized', 'That old people resist all change', 'That mobile money has failed', 'A', 
 'The passage emphasizes uneven adoption and coexistence of old and new.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The grandmother and grandson in the passage represent:', 
 'Contrasting relationships with money across generations', 'Family conflict', 'The superiority of youth', 'The wisdom of age', 'A', 
 'They embody different approaches shaped by different historical experiences.', 'Comprehension', 'medium'),

(1, 'The phrase "coexisting uneasily" suggests:', 
 'Tension and lack of integration between different economic systems', 'Peaceful harmony', 'Complete separation', 'One system dominating', 'A', 
 'This indicates the two systems exist together but with friction and misunderstanding.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'Read: "The concept of ''African time'' has long been used both defensively and offensively - by Africans explaining their perceived lack of punctuality, and by outsiders stereotyping Africans as chronically late. But beneath this cliché lies a genuine cultural difference in the experience of time itself. In many traditional African societies, time was not a commodity to be spent or saved, but a horizon of events and relationships. A meeting began when all who needed to be present had arrived, not when the clock reached a predetermined number. Conversations continued until understanding was reached, not until an arbitrary minute hand dictated. The introduction of Western industrial time - timed shifts, hourly wages, appointment schedules - created a friction that persists, as Africans navigate between these temporal worlds." The author suggests "African time" as stereotype oversimplifies:', 
 'A genuine difference in how time is experienced and valued culturally', 'The laziness of Africans', 'The superiority of Western punctuality', 'The impossibility of being on time in Africa', 'A', 
 'The passage argues the stereotype masks real cultural differences in time conception.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'According to the passage, traditional African time was oriented around:', 
 'Events and relationships rather than abstract clock measurement', 'Religious ceremonies', 'Agricultural cycles only', 'Age grades', 'A', 
 'Time was marked by significant events and relationships, not abstract units.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'The "friction" mentioned in the passage arises from:', 
 'Navigating between different temporal systems with different expectations', 'Traffic congestion', 'Disagreements about history', 'Language barriers', 'A', 
 'Friction comes from moving between traditional event-time and modern clock-time.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'Read: "The return of democracy to Nigeria in 1999 opened possibilities that had been closed for sixteen years. Newspapers multiplied, their pages filled with debates once confined to whispered conversations. Civil society organizations flourished, demanding accountability from elected officials. For a brief period, it seemed the country might fulfill the promise its independence had offered decades earlier. Yet the intervening years have complicated that optimism. Old political habits proved tenacious. Corruption adapted to new circumstances rather than disappearing. The energy of civil society met the inertia of institutions built to resist rather than respond to popular demands. The result is a democracy that is real - elections occur, governments change - but that has not yet delivered the transformation many anticipated." The passage suggests Nigeria''s democracy since 1999 has been:', 
 'Real but incomplete, achieving political change without full transformation', 'A complete failure', 'A perfect success', 'No different from military rule', 'A', 
 'The passage acknowledges real democratic gains while noting unmet expectations.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'The phrase "institutions built to resist rather than respond to popular demands" suggests:', 
 'That institutional design can hinder democratic responsiveness', 'That all institutions are bad', 'That Nigerians don''t want democracy', 'That military rule was better', 'A', 
 'This identifies structural obstacles to democratic transformation beyond individual leaders.', 'Comprehension', 'hard'),

(1, 'The passage''s tone toward Nigeria''s democratic experience is best described as:', 
 'Realistic - acknowledging both achievements and persistent challenges', 'Enthusiastically optimistic', 'Deeply pessimistic', 'Indifferent', 'A', 
 'The balanced assessment notes both progress and ongoing difficulties without extreme judgment.', 'Comprehension', 'hard');

